1
00:00:01,001 --> 00:00:02,161
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

2
00:00:02,281 --> 00:00:03,881
(ELEPHANT TRUMPETING)

3
00:00:05,801 --> 00:00:07,081
(GASPS)

4
00:00:08,961 --> 00:00:11,441
MAN: Come on. Follow me this way.

5
00:00:11,561 --> 00:00:13,121
Come and see the elephant.

6
00:00:13,601 --> 00:00:15,281
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

7
00:00:16,161 --> 00:00:17,961
Okay, I have questions.

8
00:00:26,761 --> 00:00:28,841
You never said we could travel
into parallel worlds.

9
00:00:28,961 --> 00:00:30,321
DOCTOR: Not a parallel world.

10
00:00:30,441 --> 00:00:31,561
But that's London?

11
00:00:31,721 --> 00:00:32,841
(MACHINE BEEPING)

12
00:00:32,961 --> 00:00:33,961
Our London.

13
00:00:34,081 --> 00:00:37,321
We're on the Thames,
the last great Frost Fair, 1814.

14
00:00:37,521 --> 00:00:38,561
February the fourth.

15
00:00:38,681 --> 00:00:39,761
Hang on.

16
00:00:40,001 --> 00:00:41,881
Why aren't we home?
Can't you steer this thing?

17
00:00:41,961 --> 00:00:44,481
I told you, you don't steer the TARDIS,
you reason with it.

18
00:00:44,561 --> 00:00:46,761
-BILL: How?
-Unsuccessfully, most of the time.

19
00:00:48,161 --> 00:00:49,841
She's a bad girl, this one.

20
00:00:50,241 --> 00:00:51,601
Always looking for trouble.

21
00:00:59,241 --> 00:01:00,481
DOCTOR: Oh.

22
00:01:03,241 --> 00:01:04,841
Last day before the thaw.

23
00:01:05,281 --> 00:01:07,521
Thought I'd better find
a more reliable parking spot.

24
00:01:07,881 --> 00:01:09,481
Wait, you want to go out there?

25
00:01:10,641 --> 00:01:12,401
-You don't?
-It's 1814.

26
00:01:12,521 --> 00:01:13,881
Melanin.

27
00:01:13,961 --> 00:01:16,521
-Yes?
-Slavery is still totally a thing.

28
00:01:19,721 --> 00:01:20,801
Yes, so it is.

29
00:01:20,881 --> 00:01:22,921
It might be, like, dangerous out there.

30
00:01:23,041 --> 00:01:24,641
DOCTOR: Definitely it's dangerous.

31
00:01:25,201 --> 00:01:26,561
So how do we stay out of trouble?

32
00:01:26,641 --> 00:01:28,481
Well, I'm not the right person to ask.

33
00:01:28,881 --> 00:01:31,121
Okay, when you go somewhere dangerous,
what do you take?

34
00:01:31,521 --> 00:01:33,521
First on the left, second right,

35
00:01:33,641 --> 00:01:35,921
under the stairs, past the bins,
fifth door on the left.

36
00:01:36,201 --> 00:01:37,641
-What's there?
-DOCTOR: The wardrobe.

37
00:01:37,761 --> 00:01:38,841
Pick a dress.

38
00:01:39,281 --> 00:01:41,961
So the TARDIS has dresses
and likes a bit of trouble?

39
00:01:43,281 --> 00:01:44,481
Yeah, I think I'm low key
enough for that.

40
00:01:45,001 --> 00:01:46,121
Me too.

41
00:01:46,401 --> 00:01:47,401
(CHUCKLES)

42
00:01:50,441 --> 00:01:52,841
MAN: Watch out, sir. Whoa! (GRUNTING)

43
00:02:09,961 --> 00:02:12,001
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

44
00:02:52,681 --> 00:02:54,801
Doesn't anyone notice the TARDIS?

45
00:02:54,961 --> 00:02:56,761
DOCTOR: Your species
hardly notices anything.

46
00:02:57,161 --> 00:02:58,321
(BEEPING)

47
00:03:00,521 --> 00:03:02,481
(RAPID BEEPING)

48
00:03:04,841 --> 00:03:05,961
BILL: So, what are the rules?

49
00:03:06,321 --> 00:03:07,401
Rules?

50
00:03:07,481 --> 00:03:08,601
BILL: Yeah.

51
00:03:09,401 --> 00:03:11,601
Travelling to the past,
there's got to be rules.

52
00:03:11,721 --> 00:03:14,081
If I step on a butterfly,
it could send ripples through time that,

53
00:03:14,161 --> 00:03:16,601
I mean, I'm not even born in the first
place and I could just disappear.

54
00:03:16,681 --> 00:03:18,521
Definitely. I mean,
that's what happened to Pete.

55
00:03:19,001 --> 00:03:21,001
-Pete?
-Your friend, Pete.

56
00:03:21,361 --> 00:03:23,081
He was standing there, a moment ago,

57
00:03:23,161 --> 00:03:25,561
but he stepped on a butterfly.
Now you don't even remember him.

58
00:03:27,441 --> 00:03:28,481
Shut up.

59
00:03:28,561 --> 00:03:31,321
-(LAUGHS) I'm being serious.
-Yeah, so was Pete.

60
00:03:31,401 --> 00:03:32,841
You know what I mean.

61
00:03:33,041 --> 00:03:34,801
Every choice I make in this moment,

62
00:03:34,921 --> 00:03:37,601
here and now,
could change the whole future.

63
00:03:37,681 --> 00:03:38,961
Exactly like every other
day of your life.

64
00:03:39,081 --> 00:03:41,001
The only thing to do is
to stop worrying about it.

65
00:03:41,561 --> 00:03:42,761
Mmm.

66
00:03:43,241 --> 00:03:44,241
Okay.

67
00:03:44,401 --> 00:03:45,881
If you say so.

68
00:03:46,641 --> 00:03:47,801
Petes don't worry.

69
00:03:47,881 --> 00:03:48,881
MAN: Chestnuts, sir?

70
00:03:49,001 --> 00:03:50,361
Ooh. Here you are, sir.

71
00:03:50,441 --> 00:03:53,801
Come to the Frost Fair, miss.
Only a sixpence, miss.

72
00:03:54,441 --> 00:03:56,561
(LAUGHING) Oh, my God.

73
00:03:59,161 --> 00:04:01,641
You're not stepping on a butterfly,
you're just taking a flyer.

74
00:04:07,401 --> 00:04:08,721
It's just time travel.

75
00:04:10,041 --> 00:04:11,241
Don't overthink it.

76
00:04:11,641 --> 00:04:13,961
-Is that what you said to Pete?
-Who's Pete?

77
00:04:16,361 --> 00:04:18,441
(MEN YELLING INDISTINCTLY)

78
00:04:20,601 --> 00:04:22,761
(LIVELY CHATTER)

79
00:04:46,761 --> 00:04:49,961
Yeah, no big deal.
Just walking on the Thames. (LAUGHS)

80
00:04:51,001 --> 00:04:53,361
I hope you realise
I'm going to try everything.

81
00:04:54,321 --> 00:04:55,441
Everything.

82
00:04:56,921 --> 00:05:00,561
-Tasty ox cheek, piping hot.
-Lapland mutton. Lapland mutton.

83
00:05:01,321 --> 00:05:04,401
WOMAN: Get your sheep hearts here.
Juicy, juicy sheep hearts.

84
00:05:04,521 --> 00:05:06,281
Yeah, maybe not everything.

85
00:05:06,361 --> 00:05:09,161
Oh, go on, try this.
This is my favourite.

86
00:05:09,241 --> 00:05:10,601
Your favourite?

87
00:05:10,681 --> 00:05:11,761
You've been here before?

88
00:05:11,921 --> 00:05:13,481
Oh yeah, few times.

89
00:05:14,601 --> 00:05:17,001
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

90
00:05:17,081 --> 00:05:18,761
(APPLAUSE)

91
00:05:20,041 --> 00:05:21,361
(GRUNTING)

92
00:05:22,481 --> 00:05:23,521
Get him!

93
00:05:23,601 --> 00:05:26,001
Course it's not really wrestling
unless it's in zero gravity.

94
00:05:26,121 --> 00:05:27,441
-BILL: Seriously?
-(GRUNTING)

95
00:05:27,561 --> 00:05:29,761
-With tentacles.
-Okay.

96
00:05:29,841 --> 00:05:31,281
And magic spells.

97
00:05:31,401 --> 00:05:32,401
(LAUGHING)

98
00:05:35,001 --> 00:05:36,401
(CROWD EXCLAIMING)

99
00:05:40,841 --> 00:05:42,441
-Interesting.
-What is?

100
00:05:42,761 --> 00:05:45,641
Regency England. Bit more black
than they show in the movies.

101
00:05:47,241 --> 00:05:48,681
So was Jesus.

102
00:05:48,881 --> 00:05:51,281
-History's a whitewash.
-(GASPS)

103
00:05:51,401 --> 00:05:52,681
(GRUNTING)

104
00:05:55,241 --> 00:05:57,721
(MUFFLED GRUNTING)

105
00:05:58,041 --> 00:05:59,921
(GROWLING)

106
00:06:05,481 --> 00:06:06,601
(CHEERING)

107
00:06:06,681 --> 00:06:08,521
Pub champion. Two years running.

108
00:06:09,321 --> 00:06:10,681
(SIGHS)

109
00:06:24,441 --> 00:06:25,561
Huh.

110
00:06:27,841 --> 00:06:29,801
PIE-MAN: Fresh fish pies on the ice!

111
00:06:30,841 --> 00:06:34,321
Try your luck, ladies and gentlemen,
toss for a pie.

112
00:06:34,521 --> 00:06:35,681
(COIN FLIPS)

113
00:06:37,601 --> 00:06:39,761
-(SIGHS)
-Better luck next time, miss.

114
00:06:40,201 --> 00:06:44,361
And you're sure this isn't cow brains
or sheep eyes.

115
00:06:44,441 --> 00:06:46,361
No, I've caught the fish meself, miss.

116
00:06:46,441 --> 00:06:48,761
Made it right here in the old... Hey!

117
00:06:49,201 --> 00:06:51,201
-What are you about?
-Do that again, toss the coin.

118
00:06:51,281 --> 00:06:52,801
You pay me another, I will.

119
00:06:53,281 --> 00:06:55,281
DOCTOR: Forget about the pie,
I don't want a pie.

120
00:06:55,361 --> 00:06:58,441
-I just want to see how you cheated.
-PIE-MAN: Cheated?

121
00:06:58,961 --> 00:07:00,081
Doctor.

122
00:07:00,161 --> 00:07:01,521
Don't look at me like that.

123
00:07:01,601 --> 00:07:04,481
I'm saying, you're a very good con-man.

124
00:07:05,001 --> 00:07:07,641
PIE-MAN: A what?
DOCTOR: A trickster. A swindler.

125
00:07:07,721 --> 00:07:09,441
See, I'm a bit of a thief myself.

126
00:07:09,521 --> 00:07:12,561
You know, I bet you that I could steal
anything from your shop.

127
00:07:14,681 --> 00:07:15,921
PIE-MAN: Get out!

128
00:07:17,281 --> 00:07:18,561
In theory.

129
00:07:18,641 --> 00:07:21,401
I could steal anything. In theory.

130
00:07:21,561 --> 00:07:23,601
-Doctor.
-Honestly, some people...

131
00:07:25,161 --> 00:07:26,401
More pie?

132
00:07:29,121 --> 00:07:31,201
Are there side-effects to time travel?

133
00:07:31,281 --> 00:07:32,441
Like, physical symptoms?

134
00:07:32,521 --> 00:07:34,441
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

135
00:07:34,721 --> 00:07:37,641
Sometimes, you see lights under the ice.

136
00:07:40,081 --> 00:07:43,241
Okay, so... You've seen the lights?

137
00:07:43,361 --> 00:07:44,401
Of course.

138
00:07:44,481 --> 00:07:46,201
Well, why didn't you say something?

139
00:07:46,281 --> 00:07:48,201
Well, you were enjoying yourself.

140
00:07:48,321 --> 00:07:50,481
I assumed we'd get to work eventually.

141
00:08:02,721 --> 00:08:04,081
(GRUNTING)

142
00:08:06,601 --> 00:08:08,801
(WHISTLING)

143
00:08:21,601 --> 00:08:24,801
-(GASPS, SCREAMS)
-(WATER SPLASHING)

144
00:08:27,521 --> 00:08:29,441
Are these lights electric or organic?

145
00:08:30,121 --> 00:08:31,361
Organic lights?

146
00:08:31,681 --> 00:08:32,881
Bioluminescence.

147
00:08:33,161 --> 00:08:34,841
Fireflies. Glow-worms.

148
00:08:35,601 --> 00:08:37,961
KITTY: Please, sir,
have you seen me dog?

149
00:08:39,041 --> 00:08:41,441
He was right here,
but then I looked away and he...

150
00:08:42,801 --> 00:08:44,561
Oh, it's okay. We'll help.

151
00:08:45,041 --> 00:08:46,681
Erm, what does he look like?

152
00:08:47,081 --> 00:08:48,361
He's small,

153
00:08:48,801 --> 00:08:51,081
and brown and ever so soft.

154
00:08:51,441 --> 00:08:52,641
Are you sure of that?

155
00:08:53,121 --> 00:08:55,441
That collar's for a big dog,
with long white hair.

156
00:08:56,961 --> 00:08:58,841
Nice con, though, respect.

157
00:09:00,641 --> 00:09:02,241
(GRUNTING)

158
00:09:02,561 --> 00:09:03,681
Run!

159
00:09:22,401 --> 00:09:23,441
What is it, do you think?

160
00:09:23,521 --> 00:09:24,961
Something valuable.

161
00:09:25,921 --> 00:09:26,961
Don't break it.

162
00:09:27,081 --> 00:09:28,321
What happened to the girl?

163
00:09:28,481 --> 00:09:30,561
Does it matter?
Boy's the one with your magic wand.

164
00:09:30,881 --> 00:09:32,201
Sonic screwdriver.

165
00:09:33,281 --> 00:09:34,441
How is that a screwdriver?

166
00:09:34,561 --> 00:09:35,761
In a very broad sense.

167
00:09:36,041 --> 00:09:38,241
-Oh, well, how is it sonic?
-It makes a noise.

168
00:09:39,521 --> 00:09:40,841
There they are!

169
00:09:52,081 --> 00:09:53,521
Spider! Come on!

170
00:09:54,601 --> 00:09:56,321
Kitty, come look.

171
00:09:57,121 --> 00:09:59,361
KITTY: They'll catch you
and have you transported.

172
00:09:59,441 --> 00:10:00,521
Is that what you want?

173
00:10:01,121 --> 00:10:02,321
Spider!

174
00:10:02,921 --> 00:10:04,361
Spider! Quick!

175
00:10:04,721 --> 00:10:05,841
The lights.

176
00:10:05,921 --> 00:10:07,281
I see the lights.

177
00:10:10,081 --> 00:10:11,521
Kitty! (SCREAMING)

178
00:10:14,401 --> 00:10:15,521
Stay back!

179
00:10:28,881 --> 00:10:30,001
(GRUNTING)

180
00:10:30,561 --> 00:10:31,601
(SIGHS)

181
00:10:35,721 --> 00:10:36,961
(GASPS SOFTLY)

182
00:10:46,721 --> 00:10:47,721
Save him.

183
00:10:47,841 --> 00:10:49,361
I can't. He's gone.

184
00:10:51,121 --> 00:10:54,161
Do something and save him.

185
00:10:56,961 --> 00:10:58,281
I'm sorry about your friend,

186
00:10:58,401 --> 00:10:59,761
but the danger isn't over yet.

187
00:11:00,521 --> 00:11:02,241
There must be more of you
living rough here.

188
00:11:02,321 --> 00:11:03,321
Tell me where.

189
00:11:03,401 --> 00:11:04,641
So you can take us to the magistrate?

190
00:11:04,721 --> 00:11:06,001
No, of course not!

191
00:11:06,081 --> 00:11:07,721
We're not here to arrest you,
we're here to help.

192
00:11:07,841 --> 00:11:09,601
And if you show me where you live,
we can do that.

193
00:11:09,921 --> 00:11:11,721
We? She's gone!

194
00:11:17,441 --> 00:11:19,521
(PANTING)

195
00:11:23,881 --> 00:11:24,961
(CRYING SOFTLY)

196
00:11:31,521 --> 00:11:33,121
How did you find me?

197
00:11:33,201 --> 00:11:34,401
Get used to that question.

198
00:11:34,481 --> 00:11:35,681
Oh, clever.

199
00:11:36,001 --> 00:11:37,481
You're very clever.

200
00:11:39,121 --> 00:11:40,321
What's wrong?

201
00:11:40,961 --> 00:11:42,281
What's wrong?

202
00:11:42,721 --> 00:11:44,481
Seriously? What's wrong?

203
00:11:45,681 --> 00:11:48,321
I've never seen anyone die before.

204
00:11:49,281 --> 00:11:52,521
A few hours ago, we were standing
in a garden full of dead people.

205
00:11:52,841 --> 00:11:53,961
It was different.

206
00:11:54,081 --> 00:11:56,161
-How?
-They were dead already.

207
00:11:57,361 --> 00:11:59,961
Morally and practically, that is not
a useful distinction, unlearn it.

208
00:12:00,041 --> 00:12:02,001
Don't tell me what to think.

209
00:12:02,881 --> 00:12:04,161
I'm your teacher.

210
00:12:04,401 --> 00:12:06,001
Telling you things is what I do.

211
00:12:06,081 --> 00:12:07,961
Yeah? Tell me this.

212
00:12:08,961 --> 00:12:10,281
You've seen people die before, yeah?

213
00:12:10,401 --> 00:12:11,681
-Of course.
-You still care?

214
00:12:11,761 --> 00:12:12,801
Of course I care.

215
00:12:12,881 --> 00:12:14,041
How many?

216
00:12:14,121 --> 00:12:15,281
How many what?

217
00:12:16,001 --> 00:12:17,641
If you care so much,

218
00:12:18,321 --> 00:12:20,401
tell me how many people you've seen die.

219
00:12:22,881 --> 00:12:24,161
I don't know.

220
00:12:25,641 --> 00:12:26,761
Okay.

221
00:12:28,201 --> 00:12:29,761
How many before you lost count?

222
00:12:31,241 --> 00:12:33,801
I care, Bill, but I move on.

223
00:12:34,121 --> 00:12:36,161
Yeah. How quickly?

224
00:12:37,281 --> 00:12:38,721
It's not me you're angry with.

225
00:12:38,801 --> 00:12:40,361
Have you ever killed anyone?

226
00:12:42,161 --> 00:12:44,601
There's a look in your eyes sometimes
that makes me wonder.

227
00:12:46,281 --> 00:12:47,441
Have you?

228
00:12:49,321 --> 00:12:51,481
There are situations when
the options available are limited.

229
00:12:51,561 --> 00:12:52,841
Not what I asked.

230
00:12:53,641 --> 00:12:54,881
Sometimes, the choices...

231
00:12:54,961 --> 00:12:56,801
That's not what I asked!

232
00:13:03,521 --> 00:13:04,641
Yes.

233
00:13:05,121 --> 00:13:06,241
(GASPS)

234
00:13:12,081 --> 00:13:13,281
How many?

235
00:13:17,521 --> 00:13:19,041
Don't tell me.

236
00:13:19,761 --> 00:13:21,441
You've moved on.

237
00:13:24,161 --> 00:13:25,681
And you know what happens
if I don't move on?

238
00:13:25,761 --> 00:13:26,881
More people die.

239
00:13:28,721 --> 00:13:31,161
There are kids living rough near here,

240
00:13:31,241 --> 00:13:32,881
they may well be next on the menu.

241
00:13:33,161 --> 00:13:35,761
Do you want to help me? Do you want
to stand here stamping your foot?

242
00:13:35,841 --> 00:13:39,161
Because let me tell you something,
I am 2,000 years old

243
00:13:40,321 --> 00:13:42,121
and I have never had the time

244
00:13:43,201 --> 00:13:45,281
for the luxury of outrage.

245
00:13:53,361 --> 00:13:55,041
What do you mean, "on the menu"?

246
00:14:00,441 --> 00:14:02,161
BILL: Is this where you live?

247
00:14:02,241 --> 00:14:03,521
KITTY: For now.

248
00:14:04,481 --> 00:14:06,441
BILL: But there's no one here.

249
00:14:06,561 --> 00:14:07,721
Good work.

250
00:14:11,601 --> 00:14:13,281
Except you, Dot. I can see your shoes.

251
00:14:13,601 --> 00:14:15,401
They're too big, that's why.

252
00:14:15,721 --> 00:14:18,801
Oh, I see! I get it.

253
00:14:18,881 --> 00:14:20,561
You lure people to the fair,

254
00:14:21,001 --> 00:14:22,801
and then you rob them. Very good.

255
00:14:23,281 --> 00:14:24,961
Very enterprising.

256
00:14:25,041 --> 00:14:26,281
They're all right, Dot.

257
00:14:26,721 --> 00:14:28,801
Strange, but all right.

258
00:14:29,401 --> 00:14:30,721
And that's not how it is.

259
00:14:31,201 --> 00:14:33,801
Oh, what, uh, you don't rob people?

260
00:14:33,921 --> 00:14:35,321
Of course we do.

261
00:14:35,401 --> 00:14:38,241
But bringing people to the fair,
that's by the by.

262
00:14:38,361 --> 00:14:39,561
On the side, like.

263
00:14:41,921 --> 00:14:42,921
Why?

264
00:14:43,041 --> 00:14:46,401
Why? For coin of course, why else?

265
00:14:46,521 --> 00:14:48,481
Someone pays you to promote the fair.

266
00:14:48,641 --> 00:14:50,201
Get people onto the ice.

267
00:14:52,801 --> 00:14:54,561
Who? Who pays you?

268
00:14:54,681 --> 00:14:57,121
Kitty, where's Spider?

269
00:15:00,321 --> 00:15:01,441
Spider is...

270
00:15:02,921 --> 00:15:04,001
He...

271
00:15:06,481 --> 00:15:08,561
Who's hungry? I'm hungry.

272
00:15:08,641 --> 00:15:10,761
Food! Bill, food.

273
00:15:10,881 --> 00:15:13,361
-Food is always useful. Now!
-(STAMMERING) Yeah.

274
00:15:13,441 --> 00:15:15,521
I know what you're thinking.

275
00:15:15,641 --> 00:15:18,721
But don't worry, these are stolen!

276
00:15:26,121 --> 00:15:28,001
DOCTOR: Well, eat up.

277
00:15:29,881 --> 00:15:32,521
Uh, with your permission, of course.

278
00:15:42,881 --> 00:15:45,401
"Don't suck your thumbs while I'm away.

279
00:15:45,481 --> 00:15:48,001
"The great tall tailor always comes

280
00:15:48,121 --> 00:15:51,521
"To little boys who suck their thumbs.

281
00:15:51,841 --> 00:15:53,881
"And ere they dream what he's about

282
00:15:54,401 --> 00:15:57,441
"He takes his great sharp scissors out

283
00:15:57,961 --> 00:16:00,721
"And cuts their thumbs
clean off and then..."

284
00:16:00,801 --> 00:16:02,041
You done staring yet?

285
00:16:05,961 --> 00:16:08,081
We're gonna find out
what those things are, okay?

286
00:16:08,161 --> 00:16:10,361
They're not gonna
hurt anyone else, I promise.

287
00:16:11,561 --> 00:16:12,841
I promise.

288
00:16:14,041 --> 00:16:16,961
The Doctor, he helps people.

289
00:16:17,281 --> 00:16:18,401
That's what he does.

290
00:16:18,841 --> 00:16:22,401
And you? What do you do?
Apart from shout at him.

291
00:16:23,361 --> 00:16:24,481
We were fighting.

292
00:16:26,241 --> 00:16:28,801
-It happens.
-Are you still fighting now?

293
00:16:30,881 --> 00:16:32,001
No.

294
00:16:33,441 --> 00:16:34,841
I moved on.

295
00:16:40,681 --> 00:16:45,121
Okay, I'm wondering why the Frost Fair's
on this part of the river.

296
00:16:46,001 --> 00:16:48,201
I bet that at least one of you knows

297
00:16:48,441 --> 00:16:50,561
who paid Kitty to take people
out on the ice.

298
00:16:51,041 --> 00:16:54,281
-It was bad man with a ship.
-Dottie!

299
00:16:54,561 --> 00:16:56,041
A ship, what? You mean a merchant?

300
00:16:56,321 --> 00:16:57,761
-Not that kind of ship.
-Harry!

301
00:16:57,881 --> 00:16:59,521
-What?
-KITTY: It's all right.

302
00:17:00,161 --> 00:17:01,601
You can tell him.

303
00:17:02,681 --> 00:17:04,161
It's a drawing.

304
00:17:04,841 --> 00:17:06,601
Here, on his hand.

305
00:17:07,161 --> 00:17:09,881
So, this guy, where would we find him?

306
00:17:09,961 --> 00:17:11,401
He finds us.

307
00:17:12,281 --> 00:17:14,561
But a tattoo on his hand, I mean,
we could ask around.

308
00:17:15,521 --> 00:17:19,001
Boring. I know something
that's much easier to find.

309
00:17:19,201 --> 00:17:20,761
-Where are we going?
-(EXHALES)

310
00:17:21,161 --> 00:17:23,401
All right, you guys, hang tight.

311
00:17:23,521 --> 00:17:24,641
Laters.

312
00:17:26,281 --> 00:17:27,361
I was being "all down with the kids"
there.

313
00:17:27,441 --> 00:17:28,441
Did you notice?

314
00:17:28,521 --> 00:17:30,841
-Yeah, my hair was cringing.
-Awesome.

315
00:17:32,041 --> 00:17:33,441
Please stop.

316
00:17:35,001 --> 00:17:36,401
So, what's easier to find?

317
00:17:36,481 --> 00:17:39,241
Conjecture that something's frozen
under the Thames and it's eating people.

318
00:17:39,601 --> 00:17:40,601
Okay.

319
00:17:40,721 --> 00:17:42,041
Proposal, we need to get
a closer look at it.

320
00:17:42,401 --> 00:17:45,481
-Good, yeah.
-Plan... Let's get eaten.

321
00:17:47,201 --> 00:17:48,321
Wha...

322
00:17:48,921 --> 00:17:50,401
BILL: Is this stuff safe?

323
00:17:51,361 --> 00:17:52,801
-Potentially.
-Potentially?

324
00:17:52,921 --> 00:17:54,081
What does "potentially” mean?

325
00:17:54,201 --> 00:17:55,481
Safe for the frisson of excitement.

326
00:17:56,801 --> 00:17:58,361
Right, but we're not gonna be, like,

327
00:17:58,441 --> 00:18:00,281
completely defenceless down there,
though?

328
00:18:00,361 --> 00:18:01,641
No, no, no, no.

329
00:18:02,601 --> 00:18:03,681
Well, yes, but don't worry about it.

330
00:18:04,281 --> 00:18:07,321
Why not?
What have you got up your sleeve?

331
00:18:08,001 --> 00:18:09,321
Oh, my God!

332
00:18:09,441 --> 00:18:10,881
Have you been holding out on me?

333
00:18:11,001 --> 00:18:12,441
Do you have, like, magical alien powers?

334
00:18:12,681 --> 00:18:13,801
(BLOWS)

335
00:18:15,481 --> 00:18:17,121
What, was that an impolite question?

336
00:18:18,081 --> 00:18:20,601
Why do we need diving suits
on top of the ice?

337
00:18:20,681 --> 00:18:23,681
If we're lucky,
the lights will come and take us under.

338
00:18:24,121 --> 00:18:26,001
Whatever they are, they're clever.

339
00:18:26,081 --> 00:18:27,841
When they went after the boy,

340
00:18:27,961 --> 00:18:31,601
they waited until he was away
from the crowds. By himself.

341
00:18:32,041 --> 00:18:33,121
What?

342
00:18:33,921 --> 00:18:35,241
Did you say something?

343
00:18:35,521 --> 00:18:36,841
Question is, how?

344
00:18:55,161 --> 00:18:56,361
Doctor?

345
00:19:02,401 --> 00:19:04,361
(NERVOUS SIGH)

346
00:19:05,241 --> 00:19:06,401
Doctor?

347
00:19:06,721 --> 00:19:08,641
-(BREATHING HEAVILY)
-BILL: Doctor!

348
00:19:11,801 --> 00:19:13,241
(GRUNTS)

349
00:19:14,601 --> 00:19:15,801
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

350
00:19:16,641 --> 00:19:18,521
-(BILL YELLS)
-DOCTOR: Bingo!

351
00:19:19,681 --> 00:19:20,961
(GRUNTING)

352
00:19:25,081 --> 00:19:26,121
(YELLS)

353
00:19:27,521 --> 00:19:29,561
(BUBBLING)

354
00:19:33,761 --> 00:19:35,681
(AIR HISSING)

355
00:19:39,841 --> 00:19:41,281
(INAUDIBLE)

356
00:19:48,161 --> 00:19:49,961
(CREATURE ROARING)

357
00:19:51,841 --> 00:19:53,481
(LOW GROWL)

358
00:20:04,801 --> 00:20:06,481
(CHAINS CLANKING)

359
00:20:11,681 --> 00:20:12,961
(RUMBLING)

360
00:20:15,601 --> 00:20:16,601
(GROWLING)

361
00:20:23,161 --> 00:20:25,241
(BELLOWING)

362
00:20:33,761 --> 00:20:35,481
(CREATURE SINGING MOURNFULLY)

363
00:20:50,281 --> 00:20:51,561
(SINGING CONTINUES)

364
00:20:54,721 --> 00:20:56,041
(GRUNTING)

365
00:20:56,921 --> 00:20:58,361
(EXHALES)

366
00:21:01,881 --> 00:21:03,241
(GRUNTING)

367
00:21:06,361 --> 00:21:07,521
(BOTH SIGH DEEPLY)

368
00:21:08,361 --> 00:21:10,401
DOCTOR: Stop, I know you!

369
00:21:10,721 --> 00:21:12,641
You're the cheat. I love your work!

370
00:21:15,961 --> 00:21:17,441
That sound it made.

371
00:21:18,561 --> 00:21:20,961
I couldn't hear you, but that noise...

372
00:21:21,601 --> 00:21:23,521
It was like I felt it in my bones,
you know?

373
00:21:24,961 --> 00:21:27,041
It sounded like... Like...

374
00:21:27,161 --> 00:21:28,481
Despair.

375
00:21:29,241 --> 00:21:30,721
Loneliness.

376
00:21:31,521 --> 00:21:33,841
A prisoner in chains.

377
00:21:35,041 --> 00:21:37,801
That guy, he said he caught
the fish himself.

378
00:21:38,321 --> 00:21:40,961
I bought a pie off that guy. Fish pie.

379
00:21:42,521 --> 00:21:43,881
Oh, hello!

380
00:21:45,241 --> 00:21:46,841
Aren't they magnificent.

381
00:21:47,201 --> 00:21:49,601
I ate that pie. I liked that pie.

382
00:21:50,321 --> 00:21:51,761
Definitely not carnivores.

383
00:21:52,481 --> 00:21:54,401
Which means you're co-operating
with the creature.

384
00:21:54,841 --> 00:21:57,001
Providing for him.
What do you get in return, hmm?

385
00:21:57,361 --> 00:21:59,001
What did it take for you
to evolve into that?

386
00:22:01,281 --> 00:22:03,721
The creature. Do you reckon
that's what's making London so cold?

387
00:22:04,761 --> 00:22:06,081
Very possibly.

388
00:22:06,401 --> 00:22:07,921
What kind of alien messes
with the weather?

389
00:22:08,241 --> 00:22:10,361
(CHUCKLES) You assume it's alien.

390
00:22:10,721 --> 00:22:14,481
-Of course it's alien.
-Alien, terrestrial... It's irrelevant.

391
00:22:14,561 --> 00:22:18,081
The real question is,
who's keeping it in those chains?

392
00:22:18,441 --> 00:22:21,721
And perhaps our friend here
can answer that.

393
00:22:24,721 --> 00:22:26,681
Who are ya? What do you want with me?

394
00:22:26,881 --> 00:22:28,801
The coin trick, just tell me
how to do it, please.

395
00:22:29,641 --> 00:22:30,721
Okay, not the time.

396
00:22:30,801 --> 00:22:35,921
Have you ever seen a man around here
with a tattoo of a ship?

397
00:22:37,681 --> 00:22:39,201
What's that face? Is that a no?

398
00:22:39,561 --> 00:22:41,641
Or are you against tattoos?
I'm against tattoos, too.

399
00:22:41,721 --> 00:22:43,201
I think that we are bonding.

400
00:22:43,841 --> 00:22:46,321
We're stood by the docks
and you just asked me

401
00:22:46,401 --> 00:22:47,961
if I've ever seen a man
with a tattoo of a ship.

402
00:22:48,321 --> 00:22:49,921
-Exactly.
-Fair point.

403
00:22:50,521 --> 00:22:52,921
-What point?
-Forget the tattoos.

404
00:22:53,601 --> 00:22:56,241
Have you seen anyone
acting suspiciously since the freeze?

405
00:22:56,321 --> 00:22:58,641
-(BELL TOLLING, DOG BARKING)
-Well, there's the dredges.

406
00:22:59,361 --> 00:23:00,601
The dredges?

407
00:23:00,881 --> 00:23:02,841
-PIE-MAN: There's a workhouse up river.
-MAN: Hurry up!

408
00:23:02,921 --> 00:23:05,121
There's men out there
patrolling all hours.

409
00:23:05,201 --> 00:23:06,481
Be quick about it!

410
00:23:06,881 --> 00:23:09,241
BILL: What are they dredging for?
DOCTOR: Let's find out.

411
00:23:10,041 --> 00:23:11,201
(MAN SHOUTS)

412
00:23:11,521 --> 00:23:13,121
How we getting in?

413
00:23:14,641 --> 00:23:16,201
You work for the palace.

414
00:23:16,801 --> 00:23:18,401
Haven't heard that one in a while.

415
00:23:21,841 --> 00:23:23,521
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

416
00:23:24,401 --> 00:23:26,721
Oy. How'd you get through here?

417
00:23:27,201 --> 00:23:29,601
A-ha. At last, someone in authority.

418
00:23:30,481 --> 00:23:32,281
Oh, I... I do apologise, sir.
(NERVOUS LAUGH)

419
00:23:32,801 --> 00:23:34,241
Does Lord Sutcliffe know you're here?

420
00:23:34,801 --> 00:23:36,681
Does Lord Sutcliffe know we're here?

421
00:23:37,761 --> 00:23:39,201
Does Lord Sutcliffe know we're here?

422
00:23:40,321 --> 00:23:43,201
-Lord Sutcliffe insisted we come.
-Hmm.

423
00:23:43,681 --> 00:23:45,361
-Oh, that Lord Sutcliffe, yes.
-Mmm.

424
00:23:45,441 --> 00:23:47,921
There's no arguing with Sutcliffe
when he puts his foot down.

425
00:23:48,001 --> 00:23:49,361
You better show us around.

426
00:23:49,761 --> 00:23:51,521
(PANTING) Follow me, sir.

427
00:23:52,161 --> 00:23:53,601
MAN: Take it inside!

428
00:23:57,881 --> 00:23:59,361
BILL: Why all the fuss?

429
00:23:59,681 --> 00:24:03,001
-It's just mud from the river, isn't it?
-Ah, that's one word for it.

430
00:24:03,281 --> 00:24:05,121
BILL: Is this even the right place?

431
00:24:05,361 --> 00:24:07,201
Creature's almost a mile away.

432
00:24:07,361 --> 00:24:09,161
The creature's head
is almost a mile away.

433
00:24:09,601 --> 00:24:11,201
I assume we're now at the other end.

434
00:24:12,481 --> 00:24:15,521
These men, why do we trust them?

435
00:24:16,081 --> 00:24:18,881
-Hired them all myself, sir.
-Ah, and why do I trust you?

436
00:24:19,521 --> 00:24:20,561
Sir?

437
00:24:20,641 --> 00:24:22,361
You understand how important
this is, yes?

438
00:24:22,721 --> 00:24:24,721
It's imperative that no one discovers

439
00:24:24,801 --> 00:24:26,641
where the stuff goes
when it leaves here.

440
00:24:26,721 --> 00:24:28,321
Oh, I know that, sir.

441
00:24:28,441 --> 00:24:30,521
-We use unmarked cars.
-And are they ever followed?

442
00:24:31,081 --> 00:24:32,561
-Oh no, sir.
-Have you checked this personally?

443
00:24:32,641 --> 00:24:34,121
-Oh yes, sir.
-All the way to Hampton?

444
00:24:34,721 --> 00:24:36,641
No, to the steel mill, sir.

445
00:24:37,401 --> 00:24:40,721
-Hampton's code for the steel mill.
-Code?

446
00:24:41,041 --> 00:24:43,201
Yes, we need to use code,
otherwise anyone can walk in here

447
00:24:43,281 --> 00:24:44,761
and get you blabbing away like a fool.

448
00:24:45,401 --> 00:24:46,801
That's a good point, sir.

449
00:24:48,281 --> 00:24:52,321
Now, these men,
what do they know of this material?

450
00:24:52,921 --> 00:24:54,241
No more than I do, sir.

451
00:24:55,681 --> 00:24:58,241
Yes, but you are someone
who knows more than he tells.

452
00:24:58,881 --> 00:25:00,321
I'm not one to speculate.

453
00:25:01,121 --> 00:25:03,721
But you can't help it
because you are a man of intelligence.

454
00:25:04,561 --> 00:25:08,321
Well, they won't let us smoke in here
so I assume it's fuel.

455
00:25:08,801 --> 00:25:10,241
Fuel for the furnaces, sir.

456
00:25:10,881 --> 00:25:12,481
Excellent reasoning.

457
00:25:12,881 --> 00:25:15,841
Lord Sutcliffe appreciates
an inquiring mind.

458
00:25:15,921 --> 00:25:18,001
(CHUCKLES) Well, I keep me ear
to the ground, you know.

459
00:25:18,081 --> 00:25:20,001
And what does the ground say these days?

460
00:25:22,561 --> 00:25:25,881
That this stuff burns
a thousand times longer than coal.

461
00:25:27,481 --> 00:25:28,881
DOCTOR: Very good.

462
00:25:30,041 --> 00:25:32,961
Hotter too.
Hotter than they can measure.

463
00:25:35,001 --> 00:25:36,281
Excellent.

464
00:25:36,961 --> 00:25:38,441
First class.

465
00:25:39,041 --> 00:25:41,761
-I'm right, aren't I, sir?
-Oh, there's no stopping you.

466
00:25:41,841 --> 00:25:44,161
You keep this up, and you won't be
working in this yard for very long.

467
00:25:44,361 --> 00:25:46,161
-Oh, you think not?
-Oh, I can almost guarantee it.

468
00:25:46,961 --> 00:25:48,881
(CHUCKLES) You know what else they say?

469
00:25:49,441 --> 00:25:52,081
They say it even burns under water.

470
00:25:53,601 --> 00:25:54,881
No sh...

471
00:25:55,321 --> 00:25:56,601
(HORSE WHINNYING)

472
00:25:56,801 --> 00:26:00,321
BILL: So, this guy has a pet monster
that turns people into fuel

473
00:26:00,441 --> 00:26:02,761
and we're just walking up at his door?

474
00:26:03,121 --> 00:26:05,281
-That's his door, this is us walking.
-(BELL RINGING)

475
00:26:05,521 --> 00:26:07,881
If we're going to stop him,
I need to know where he started.

476
00:26:08,961 --> 00:26:10,521
-Meaning?
-Which planet.

477
00:26:10,681 --> 00:26:11,761
Which planet?

478
00:26:14,161 --> 00:26:17,681
-So, you think Sutcliffe is an alien?
-Possibly.

479
00:26:18,041 --> 00:26:19,361
Because the creature is an alien.

480
00:26:19,641 --> 00:26:23,441
It certainly appears to be producing
fuel suitable for interstellar travel.

481
00:26:25,841 --> 00:26:27,041
By the way, Bill...

482
00:26:29,041 --> 00:26:32,441
-I need you to leave the talking to me.
-Why?

483
00:26:33,441 --> 00:26:34,721
Because you have a temper.

484
00:26:35,121 --> 00:26:37,761
(STAMMERS) Okay, well,
I lost it a tiny bit.

485
00:26:38,161 --> 00:26:39,761
You're about to meet a man,
alien or otherwise,

486
00:26:39,841 --> 00:26:41,441
for whom human beings are raw material.

487
00:26:42,721 --> 00:26:44,401
Who grinds up children for profit.

488
00:26:44,881 --> 00:26:47,921
What we're here for is one thing.
Information.

489
00:26:48,801 --> 00:26:52,281
You get that with diplomacy and tact,
charm, if necessary.

490
00:26:53,121 --> 00:26:54,201
Okay.

491
00:26:55,681 --> 00:26:56,921
I get it.

492
00:26:58,401 --> 00:27:03,281
Always remember, Bill.
Passion fights, but reason wins.

493
00:27:03,361 --> 00:27:04,641
(DOOR OPENS)

494
00:27:05,721 --> 00:27:08,481
Dr Disco from the Fairford Club.

495
00:27:08,641 --> 00:27:11,201
Obviously, one aspires to membership

496
00:27:11,281 --> 00:27:13,361
but to actually be considered for...

497
00:27:15,841 --> 00:27:18,161
Who... Who let this creature in here?

498
00:27:18,241 --> 00:27:21,201
On your feet, girl,
in the presence of your betters.

499
00:27:24,241 --> 00:27:25,241
(DOCTOR GRUNTS)

500
00:27:27,841 --> 00:27:32,001
He's human. Thirty-one years of age.
Low in iron.

501
00:27:32,161 --> 00:27:35,121
Yeah, that was pretty convincing racism
for an extra-terrestrial.

502
00:27:35,201 --> 00:27:36,761
My thoughts exactly.

503
00:27:38,241 --> 00:27:42,161
Oh, hello. Er, can I just say
this is very unlike me.

504
00:27:42,241 --> 00:27:45,281
-I don't normally do this.
-Er, yeah, he was aiming for charming.

505
00:27:45,441 --> 00:27:46,681
Basically.

506
00:27:48,721 --> 00:27:50,081
LORD SUTCLIFFE: Well...

507
00:27:52,441 --> 00:27:54,081
You're not from the Fairford Club.

508
00:27:54,201 --> 00:27:55,921
The creature in the river,
where did it come from?

509
00:27:56,001 --> 00:27:57,841
Who the devil are you people?

510
00:27:57,921 --> 00:27:59,841
-Where did it come from?
-Nowhere.

511
00:28:00,281 --> 00:28:01,601
It's always been there.

512
00:28:01,681 --> 00:28:04,001
The secret's been passed down
in the family since...

513
00:28:04,281 --> 00:28:05,361
I don't know when.

514
00:28:05,441 --> 00:28:07,601
As far back as records go.

515
00:28:07,681 --> 00:28:09,641
And tell me, do you also keep a record
of how many it's killed?

516
00:28:09,761 --> 00:28:10,761
Please.

517
00:28:11,681 --> 00:28:13,361
People know the ice is dangerous,

518
00:28:13,441 --> 00:28:15,601
yet they will insist
on their festivities.

519
00:28:15,681 --> 00:28:16,961
That's hardly my fault.

520
00:28:17,081 --> 00:28:18,241
Don't sell yourself short.

521
00:28:18,321 --> 00:28:20,001
This is the biggest Frost Fair
in decades.

522
00:28:20,601 --> 00:28:23,201
-That's down to you.
-It is?

523
00:28:24,481 --> 00:28:27,041
Man holding me has a tattoo
on his left hand.

524
00:28:27,441 --> 00:28:29,041
That's not all, is it?

525
00:28:29,441 --> 00:28:32,481
The circus performers,
the elephant, it's all you.

526
00:28:34,641 --> 00:28:37,281
I made the most of the situation.

527
00:28:37,721 --> 00:28:40,641
It's the first proper freeze
it's caused in years.

528
00:28:40,801 --> 00:28:43,521
Why? Production down, huh?

529
00:28:44,001 --> 00:28:45,201
Not enough people dying.

530
00:28:45,281 --> 00:28:48,801
Girl, you show the ignorance
of all your kind.

531
00:28:49,121 --> 00:28:52,721
Without that beast,
my mills would rely on coal mines.

532
00:28:52,961 --> 00:28:55,361
Men die in coal mines all the time.

533
00:28:55,481 --> 00:28:56,801
I preferred it when you were alien.

534
00:28:58,001 --> 00:28:59,121
When I was...

535
00:29:00,281 --> 00:29:01,881
Well, that explained
the lack of humanity.

536
00:29:03,321 --> 00:29:05,681
What makes you so sure
that your life is worth more

537
00:29:05,761 --> 00:29:06,961
than those people out there on the ice?

538
00:29:07,041 --> 00:29:08,841
Is it the money?
The accident of birth

539
00:29:10,321 --> 00:29:11,921
that put you inside the big,
fancy house?

540
00:29:12,001 --> 00:29:15,121
I help move this country forward.

541
00:29:15,841 --> 00:29:18,721
I move this empire forward.

542
00:29:18,841 --> 00:29:20,721
DOCTOR: Human progress
isn't measured by industry.

543
00:29:22,001 --> 00:29:24,761
It's measured by the value you
place on a life.

544
00:29:26,081 --> 00:29:27,641
An unimportant life.

545
00:29:28,921 --> 00:29:30,641
A life without privilege.

546
00:29:30,721 --> 00:29:34,041
The boy who died on the river,
that boy's value is your value.

547
00:29:34,481 --> 00:29:39,681
That's what defines an age.
That's what defines a species.

548
00:29:43,041 --> 00:29:44,481
What a beautiful speech.

549
00:29:45,121 --> 00:29:50,041
The rhythm and, and vocabulary...
Quite outstanding.

550
00:29:52,001 --> 00:29:56,441
It's enough to move anyone
with an ounce of compassion.

551
00:29:59,361 --> 00:30:01,401
So it's really not your day, is it?

552
00:30:02,561 --> 00:30:04,641
If they know about the beast,
then others must, too.

553
00:30:04,761 --> 00:30:06,241
We bring the plan forward.

554
00:30:06,321 --> 00:30:08,001
-When, sir?
-LORD SUTCLIFFE: Now.

555
00:30:08,161 --> 00:30:09,361
In daylight.

556
00:30:12,001 --> 00:30:13,281
(GRUNTING)

557
00:30:23,201 --> 00:30:24,561
-(HORSE NEIGHS)
-(WHIP CRACKS)

558
00:30:24,641 --> 00:30:26,521
No time for outrage.

559
00:30:26,961 --> 00:30:28,721
Never had time for anything else, right?

560
00:30:28,801 --> 00:30:30,001
Don't be smug.

561
00:30:30,321 --> 00:30:31,961
Smug belongs to me.

562
00:30:34,881 --> 00:30:36,761
Are you really 2,000 years old?

563
00:30:38,241 --> 00:30:39,361
Why?

564
00:30:40,601 --> 00:30:41,841
I just

565
00:30:42,001 --> 00:30:44,001
wanted to know how long it takes

566
00:30:44,121 --> 00:30:46,321
before you can make a speech
like the one you just made.

567
00:30:47,361 --> 00:30:48,801
It's worth the wait.

568
00:30:50,841 --> 00:30:52,441
(PEOPLE SHOUTING)

569
00:31:00,721 --> 00:31:01,921
-DOCTOR: Trouble.
-Out!

570
00:31:10,161 --> 00:31:11,201
MAN: Get in!

571
00:31:11,601 --> 00:31:13,121
Sit down and shut up!

572
00:31:13,881 --> 00:31:14,881
Could be rum.

573
00:31:16,081 --> 00:31:19,001
-Rum came in barrels.
-(BOTH GRUNT)

574
00:31:19,641 --> 00:31:21,121
-Smell that.
-(GROANS)

575
00:31:21,201 --> 00:31:23,921
It's homemade rocket fuel
redeployed as explosive.

576
00:31:24,881 --> 00:31:26,201
It's a little reckless, don't you think?

577
00:31:26,681 --> 00:31:28,521
Half the fair disappears into the river.

578
00:31:28,921 --> 00:31:30,881
The secret of your success
won't be a secret any more.

579
00:31:31,161 --> 00:31:33,521
Hardly. The city will pause to mourn

580
00:31:33,601 --> 00:31:35,601
a fireworks display gone
tragically awry,

581
00:31:35,681 --> 00:31:37,921
and the creature will be fed.

582
00:31:38,521 --> 00:31:42,001
By spring, this will be a footnote
in history.

583
00:31:42,241 --> 00:31:45,201
That is progress.

584
00:31:45,841 --> 00:31:48,081
They're bringing the elephant
out presently.

585
00:31:48,161 --> 00:31:49,681
You won't get bigger crowds than that,

586
00:31:49,761 --> 00:31:52,561
so make sure you're off the ice by noon.

587
00:31:52,641 --> 00:31:53,921
Noon?

588
00:31:54,041 --> 00:31:55,681
There's no way you can keep us here
that long.

589
00:31:55,761 --> 00:31:57,521
We'll just scream our heads off.

590
00:31:57,601 --> 00:32:00,321
-No, no, please, please, please...
-(SCREAMING) Help!

591
00:32:00,481 --> 00:32:02,241
(CROWD EXCLAIMING)

592
00:32:03,121 --> 00:32:05,041
-(CROWD CHEERING)
-(GRUNTING)

593
00:32:05,121 --> 00:32:06,401
MAN: Sixpence to the water man...

594
00:32:06,561 --> 00:32:08,601
(CONTINUES SCREAMING)

595
00:32:12,481 --> 00:32:14,881
(PANTING, COUGHING)

596
00:32:14,961 --> 00:32:16,641
If you're quite finished,
I could use some help.

597
00:32:16,761 --> 00:32:17,881
What are you...

598
00:32:18,001 --> 00:32:19,361
(BOTH GRUNT)

599
00:32:19,441 --> 00:32:21,841
-Sonic screwdriver. Inside pocket.
-Oh. Okay.

600
00:32:21,921 --> 00:32:24,001
(BOTH GRUNTING)

601
00:32:29,401 --> 00:32:31,161
(STRAINING)

602
00:32:35,201 --> 00:32:36,241
-DOCTOR: Can you...
-(GRUNTS)

603
00:32:36,321 --> 00:32:39,041
-Yes! Yes!
-(PANTING) Okay.

604
00:32:39,201 --> 00:32:40,961
-(BOTH GRUNTING)
-BILL: Okay.

605
00:32:42,641 --> 00:32:44,641
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

606
00:32:46,841 --> 00:32:47,841
Um, Doctor...

607
00:32:47,921 --> 00:32:49,121
DOCTOR: Huh?

608
00:32:50,081 --> 00:32:51,361
Oh, hello.

609
00:32:52,321 --> 00:32:54,601
-BILL: How are you doing that?
-Er... Er...

610
00:32:57,281 --> 00:32:58,881
Sonic screwdriver.

611
00:32:59,201 --> 00:33:00,321
It makes a noise.

612
00:33:00,481 --> 00:33:02,321
That's how the fish choose their victim.

613
00:33:03,001 --> 00:33:04,961
That's how they know they've isolated
someone on the ice.

614
00:33:05,281 --> 00:33:07,281
Erm, better question,
why are you doing that?

615
00:33:07,681 --> 00:33:09,281
Just... Just a little more.

616
00:33:09,561 --> 00:33:11,321
(CROWD CHATTERING)

617
00:33:15,921 --> 00:33:17,041
What are you...

618
00:33:17,921 --> 00:33:19,001
Give me that!

619
00:33:19,441 --> 00:33:20,481
(GRUNTS)

620
00:33:20,561 --> 00:33:21,561
(WHIRRING CONTINUES)

621
00:33:22,041 --> 00:33:23,441
(EXCLAIMING)

622
00:33:26,561 --> 00:33:27,601
What the...

623
00:33:27,681 --> 00:33:28,681
Turn it off.
There's a button on the side.

624
00:33:31,441 --> 00:33:32,481
Here! Give it here!

625
00:33:34,041 --> 00:33:35,121
(SCREAMS)

626
00:33:36,481 --> 00:33:38,241
I'm afraid it has a knack to it.

627
00:33:39,441 --> 00:33:40,921
-(GASPS)
- (ICE CRACKING)

628
00:33:44,001 --> 00:33:45,561
(PANTING)

629
00:33:46,561 --> 00:33:47,681
Bill?

630
00:33:47,841 --> 00:33:51,921
-Miss Potts, I need you with me.
-I... I...

631
00:33:52,201 --> 00:33:54,761
Things to do, Bill, decisions to make.
What are we going to do about Tiny?

632
00:33:56,121 --> 00:33:57,601
-Tiny?
-The creature.

633
00:33:58,241 --> 00:34:00,161
The Loch Ness monster.
The naughty little mermaid.

634
00:34:00,241 --> 00:34:01,441
Are we just going to leave
her down there?

635
00:34:01,881 --> 00:34:03,321
Well, we can't set her free.

636
00:34:04,401 --> 00:34:06,961
She could burst up out of the water
and eat a hundred people

637
00:34:07,041 --> 00:34:08,481
right off of South Bank.

638
00:34:08,561 --> 00:34:11,441
-She could eat half of London!
-She might. It's a risk.

639
00:34:12,641 --> 00:34:15,561
-So, what do you want to do, Bill?
-We already know the answers.

640
00:34:16,561 --> 00:34:18,721
-Why are you even asking?
-I don't know the answers.

641
00:34:19,001 --> 00:34:20,361
Only idiots know the answers.

642
00:34:20,841 --> 00:34:23,721
But if your future is built
on the suffering of that creature,

643
00:34:23,961 --> 00:34:25,281
what's your future worth?

644
00:34:29,121 --> 00:34:30,481
Why is it up to me?

645
00:34:30,561 --> 00:34:32,001
Because it can't be up to me.

646
00:34:32,121 --> 00:34:35,321
Your people, your planet I serve
at the pleasure of the human race,

647
00:34:35,401 --> 00:34:37,601
and right now, that's you.
Give me an order.

648
00:34:38,721 --> 00:34:40,361
Not long till noon.

649
00:34:41,321 --> 00:34:42,681
I need an order.

650
00:34:54,241 --> 00:34:57,601
-(CREATURE SINGS MOURNFULLY)
-Save her.

651
00:35:00,361 --> 00:35:03,281
I'll take care of this,
you get everyone off the ice.

652
00:35:03,721 --> 00:35:05,921
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

653
00:35:08,161 --> 00:35:11,001
-Need help. Need it now. You in?
-Where's your friend?

654
00:35:11,401 --> 00:35:13,281
-Not here.
-What's he doing?

655
00:35:13,401 --> 00:35:16,441
Not sure, but whatever it is,
I don't think we're going to miss it.

656
00:35:16,921 --> 00:35:18,561
The thaw! The thaw is here!

657
00:35:18,841 --> 00:35:20,361
A lady fell through the ice!

658
00:35:20,441 --> 00:35:22,081
(ALL CLAMOURING)

659
00:35:24,761 --> 00:35:26,241
Quick! Get to the shore!

660
00:35:30,441 --> 00:35:31,641
WOMAN: The ice is melting!

661
00:35:31,721 --> 00:35:33,441
(CLAMOURING)

662
00:35:36,761 --> 00:35:39,361
It's a mistake! The ice isn't melting!

663
00:35:40,201 --> 00:35:42,201
I swear to you. There's no thaw!

664
00:35:43,561 --> 00:35:44,681
(CLAMOURING CONTINUES)

665
00:35:44,921 --> 00:35:45,921
Argh!

666
00:35:46,241 --> 00:35:47,681
The ice is melting!

667
00:35:48,161 --> 00:35:51,201
Quickly, quickly. That's it.

668
00:35:58,281 --> 00:36:01,601
LORD SUTCLIFFE: Come on! Hurry! Come on!

669
00:36:02,721 --> 00:36:04,441
Something's happened.
They've got the word out.

670
00:36:04,521 --> 00:36:05,881
We blow it now.

671
00:36:07,841 --> 00:36:09,081
Not yet.

672
00:36:11,201 --> 00:36:12,801
-The ice is melting!
-Harriet.

673
00:36:13,601 --> 00:36:15,321
-Run.
-But there's still people...

674
00:36:15,401 --> 00:36:16,801
Forget them. There's no time.

675
00:36:17,121 --> 00:36:18,241
Kitty?

676
00:36:18,361 --> 00:36:19,481
Run.

677
00:36:20,161 --> 00:36:21,481
Now!

678
00:36:27,841 --> 00:36:28,921
(GRUNTS)

679
00:36:31,561 --> 00:36:33,481
(WHIRRING)

680
00:36:33,961 --> 00:36:35,801
(EXPLOSIONS)

681
00:36:36,641 --> 00:36:37,761
What?

682
00:36:40,641 --> 00:36:41,801
(EXPLOSION)

683
00:36:42,881 --> 00:36:44,961
(EXPLOSIONS IN DISTANCE)

684
00:36:46,881 --> 00:36:48,841
(SCREAMS) Out of my way!

685
00:36:53,241 --> 00:36:54,521
Quick! Get to the shore!

686
00:36:58,241 --> 00:36:59,681
(AIR HISSING)

687
00:37:00,801 --> 00:37:02,881
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

688
00:37:14,561 --> 00:37:16,001
(ICE BREAKING)

689
00:37:25,281 --> 00:37:27,041
(CREATURE GROWLS)

690
00:37:31,681 --> 00:37:33,321
(GASPING)

691
00:37:33,441 --> 00:37:34,561
(SCREAMS)

692
00:37:36,161 --> 00:37:38,041
BILL: Doctor! Doctor!

693
00:37:38,401 --> 00:37:39,561
Bill!

694
00:37:42,201 --> 00:37:43,241
Bill!

695
00:37:43,681 --> 00:37:44,801
You did it!

696
00:37:44,921 --> 00:37:46,081
She's free!

697
00:37:52,001 --> 00:37:53,001
(STRAINING)

698
00:38:05,001 --> 00:38:06,721
(ROARS)

699
00:38:10,241 --> 00:38:11,361
Go.

700
00:38:12,001 --> 00:38:13,201
Where will she go?

701
00:38:13,281 --> 00:38:14,561
Somewhere cold, I imagine.

702
00:38:15,361 --> 00:38:18,481
Hopefully, she's smart enough
to avoid you lot now.

703
00:38:18,561 --> 00:38:20,321
You... What if she isn't?

704
00:38:20,641 --> 00:38:22,721
What if we just, like, doomed Greenland?

705
00:38:23,961 --> 00:38:25,321
I'll check in on Greenland.

706
00:38:29,921 --> 00:38:31,481
How long is she?

707
00:38:34,681 --> 00:38:36,321
(GASPS) Aw...

708
00:38:38,601 --> 00:38:40,481
-(CHUCKLES)
-(CREATURE SINGS)

709
00:38:41,921 --> 00:38:43,961
(HIGH-PITCHED WAIL)

710
00:38:44,281 --> 00:38:45,881
Can you hear that?

711
00:38:48,321 --> 00:38:50,361
(CREATURE SINGING)

712
00:38:52,161 --> 00:38:53,441
Hattie, look!

713
00:38:57,441 --> 00:38:59,161
(BELL RINGING)

714
00:38:59,481 --> 00:39:01,001
No pinching anything, you hear me?

715
00:39:02,041 --> 00:39:04,641
And no staring like gapeseeds
when the lady talks peculiar.

716
00:39:05,481 --> 00:39:07,201
-It's rude.
-(DOOR OPENS)

717
00:39:08,361 --> 00:39:11,881
Get a load of you lot!
Cute house. Come in.

718
00:39:16,241 --> 00:39:17,721
You gonna tell us what we're here for?

719
00:39:18,681 --> 00:39:20,121
A very long time I hope.

720
00:39:31,681 --> 00:39:33,201
-Go on!
-(LAUGHS)

721
00:39:33,281 --> 00:39:34,401
Eat as much as you like.

722
00:39:34,561 --> 00:39:35,681
(BLOWS)

723
00:39:41,401 --> 00:39:43,801
Er, you boy, remind me,
what's your name?

724
00:39:44,161 --> 00:39:45,281
(MUFFLED) Perry.

725
00:39:46,401 --> 00:39:49,161
Perry. His name's Perry. Why?

726
00:39:50,961 --> 00:39:54,361
Er, apparently, Lord Sutcliffe's
long-lost heir can't be a girl.

727
00:40:05,961 --> 00:40:07,961
(WHOOSHING)

728
00:40:11,041 --> 00:40:13,001
BILL: We must have
changed something, right?

729
00:40:13,281 --> 00:40:15,561
I mean, people saw a monster
in the Thames.

730
00:40:16,681 --> 00:40:18,361
Oh, it doesn't look any different.

731
00:40:20,201 --> 00:40:21,801
-(SIGHS)
-All right.

732
00:40:22,841 --> 00:40:24,001
Here you go.

733
00:40:24,841 --> 00:40:26,121
Here's your tea.

734
00:40:27,081 --> 00:40:29,961
And I put a bit of coffee in it as well
just to give it some flavour.

735
00:40:30,721 --> 00:40:34,601
See? It's much better
when you stick to your oath.

736
00:40:38,601 --> 00:40:42,521
Oh, sir, no. This is unacceptable.
This is beyond unacceptable.

737
00:40:42,601 --> 00:40:44,641
-This is naughty.
-Language.

738
00:40:44,761 --> 00:40:47,081
BILL: I don't get it. "London 1814."

739
00:40:48,041 --> 00:40:50,401
"Monster." "Sea creature." "Serpent.”

740
00:40:51,201 --> 00:40:53,281
"Really, really big fish." Nothing.

741
00:40:54,081 --> 00:40:56,961
Sir, you said you wouldn't be
going off-world.

742
00:40:57,761 --> 00:41:00,241
Do these look like off-world
clothes to you?

743
00:41:00,561 --> 00:41:02,481
But, sir, you said
you'd be coming back to your office.

744
00:41:02,761 --> 00:41:04,201
Look. Here I am.

745
00:41:04,801 --> 00:41:09,761
I'm in my office. I'm drinking my tea,
in my specially-chosen tea clothes.

746
00:41:09,921 --> 00:41:11,201
BILL: I don't understand.

747
00:41:11,521 --> 00:41:13,081
How could it not have
been headline news?

748
00:41:13,161 --> 00:41:15,321
Never underestimate
the collective human ability

749
00:41:15,401 --> 00:41:17,121
to overlook the inexplicable.

750
00:41:17,241 --> 00:41:20,841
Also, the Frost Fair involved
a lot of day drinking. May 17

751
00:41:23,161 --> 00:41:25,481
You can always rely upon the papers
to miss a headline.

752
00:41:25,801 --> 00:41:27,321
(BILL READING)

753
00:41:28,881 --> 00:41:31,241
"Shock as steel fortune
is passed to street urchin.”

754
00:41:31,841 --> 00:41:34,921
Sir, we need to talk. Your oath.

755
00:41:35,361 --> 00:41:36,481
-Give us a coin.
-What?

756
00:41:36,681 --> 00:41:39,921
"The new Lord Sutcliffe was found
starving on London's streets.

757
00:41:40,641 --> 00:41:42,121
"Inheritance was contested."

758
00:41:42,681 --> 00:41:45,441
Everyone got super mad.
Blah, blah, blah...

759
00:41:45,721 --> 00:41:47,641
"Urchin boy deemed legitimate."

760
00:41:48,161 --> 00:41:49,641
Oh, my God, it worked!

761
00:41:50,561 --> 00:41:53,081
You did it. You saved them.

762
00:41:54,681 --> 00:41:55,841
You did.

763
00:41:56,481 --> 00:42:00,481
-You gave the order, boss.
-Sir...

764
00:42:02,881 --> 00:42:04,201
DOCTOR: Give me a coin.

765
00:42:05,241 --> 00:42:06,561
We'll toss for it.

766
00:42:06,921 --> 00:42:08,801
Heads the TARDIS stays put...

767
00:42:09,721 --> 00:42:10,921
Tails...

768
00:42:12,321 --> 00:42:13,761
You leave me alone.

769
00:42:17,961 --> 00:42:19,801
Leave him alone. (SCOFFS)

770
00:42:19,881 --> 00:42:21,601
Chance would be a fine thing.

771
00:42:21,721 --> 00:42:23,001
Leave me alone.

772
00:42:23,241 --> 00:42:25,321
How's about that for a new idea?

773
00:42:25,761 --> 00:42:27,961
Never asked to be reassembled, did I?

774
00:42:28,281 --> 00:42:29,961
(LOUD KNOCKING)

775
00:42:31,081 --> 00:42:32,321
Knocking.

776
00:42:33,961 --> 00:42:35,521
What's that about?

777
00:42:36,641 --> 00:42:38,761
No one's gonna open the door
just because you're knocking.

778
00:42:38,881 --> 00:42:40,921
(LOUD BANGING)

779
00:42:41,241 --> 00:42:43,841
Oh, getting cocky now, are you?

780
00:42:43,961 --> 00:42:46,281
Why? What do you think you know?

781
00:42:48,961 --> 00:42:50,521
What has he told you?

782
00:42:50,601 --> 00:42:52,201
(LOUD BANGING)

783
00:42:52,321 --> 00:42:54,921
Because yeah,
he might have a little friend now

784
00:42:55,041 --> 00:42:57,081
and yeah, he may be a little
bit distracted,

785
00:42:57,161 --> 00:42:58,361
but I'll tell you something,

786
00:42:58,441 --> 00:43:00,001
I'm still here!

787
00:43:00,321 --> 00:43:01,721
And as long as I'm still here,

788
00:43:01,801 --> 00:43:04,161
you are going nowhere!

789
00:43:04,441 --> 00:43:06,601
-(LOUD BANGING)
-(WHIMPERING)

790
00:43:11,801 --> 00:43:13,441
Are you looking for somewhere to live?

791
00:43:15,521 --> 00:43:16,601
That's your house?

792
00:43:16,841 --> 00:43:18,401
Sharing, yeah. Six of us.

793
00:43:18,681 --> 00:43:20,681
-How do you get into the tower?
-You don't.

794
00:43:21,121 --> 00:43:23,041
-What's that noise?
-(THUNDER CRACKING)

795
00:43:23,161 --> 00:43:24,521
There's a massive mystery going on.

796
00:43:25,241 --> 00:43:27,001
See you in the morning. (CHOKES)

797
00:43:28,041 --> 00:43:29,761
The house is eating people.

798
00:43:30,321 --> 00:43:31,361
(THUNDER CRASHES)

799
00:43:32,841 --> 00:43:34,881
No, no, no. There's something in here.

800
00:43:35,241 --> 00:43:36,961
-Come back, hey!
-(SCREAMS)

801
00:43:37,441 --> 00:43:40,321
You signed the contract.
It's time to pay.

802
00:43:40,961 --> 00:43:42,881
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

